
library frequently_asked;

class QA {
  final int id;
  final String question;
  final String answer;
  const QA({required this.id, required this.question, required this.answer});
}

class QATheme {
  final String title;
  final List<QA> items;
  const QATheme({required this.title, required this.items});
}

// Top-level list of all themes with their Q&A.
const List<QATheme> frequentlyAskedData = [

  QATheme(title: "Recognition & Self‑Awareness", items: [
    QA(id: 1, question: "How do I know if all this irritability, anger or fatigue is just stress — or actual depression?", answer: "When irritability or fatigue lingers for weeks and starts affecting your sleep, motivation, or relationships, it’s likely more than stress. Stress usually fades after rest or problem‑solving; depression doesn’t. Men often experience depression as frustration or exhaustion rather than sadness. Start by noting how long it’s been happening and how much joy or focus you’ve lost. If it’s lasting, speak to a GP or therapist — not as a weakness, but as a health check for your mind. Depression is highly treatable, and recovery often begins with honest awareness."),
    QA(id: 2, question: "Why do I feel empty or numb instead of sad when I’m depressed?", answer: "Emotional numbness is the mind’s way of self‑protection when it’s overwhelmed. For many men, sadness feels unsafe to express, so the brain “shuts down” emotions instead. That’s why you might feel detached or hollow rather than tearful. It’s not a sign of hopelessness — it’s a signal you’ve been carrying too much for too long. Reconnection happens through safe expression: journaling, therapy, mindful breathing, or calm conversations about what’s missing. Gradually, numbness fades and genuine emotion — including calm, contentment, or peace — begins to return."),
    QA(id: 3, question: "Could my constant tiredness or poor sleep be a mental‑health issue rather than a lifestyle problem?", answer: "Yes. Mental strain and anxiety can quietly disrupt your body’s rhythms, even if you think you’re “just tired.” Chronic fatigue often means your nervous system is stuck in overdrive — always alert, never resting. Improving sleep starts with calming your mind before bedtime: gentle breathing, no screens, and reflection instead of rumination. If you wake up tired even after full sleep, consider stress management or professional support. Once your mind relaxes, your body will follow. Rest is not laziness — it’s recovery for your mental circuits."),
    QA(id: 4, question: "I’m withdrawing from friends and don’t enjoy things anymore — is that a red flag?", answer: "Yes, especially if it’s been more than two weeks. Isolation and loss of interest are core signals your emotional energy is low. For men, it often starts subtly: skipping social plans, losing drive for hobbies, avoiding calls. That’s your mind’s version of a “check engine” light. You don’t have to force socialising — just start small. Send one message, go for a short walk, listen to music that once moved you. Connection rekindles motivation. Recovery starts with micro‑actions, not massive change."),
    QA(id: 5, question: "Is heavy drinking a coping mechanism or just my way to unwind?", answer: "It depends on the motive. If alcohol is your only way to relax or shut off racing thoughts, it’s likely become emotional self‑medication. Drinking numbs short‑term stress but worsens sleep, mood, and anxiety after. That cycle quietly fuels depression. Real relaxation feels replenishing, not regretful. Try replacing one drink night a week with something that restores — a long drive, music, a cold shower, or a walk. Each time you face tension without alcohol, your brain relearns resilience. The goal isn’t perfection — it’s freedom."),
    QA(id: 6, question: "I’m not sad, just constantly restless or tense — could that be anxiety?", answer: "Yes. Anxiety in men often shows as restlessness, racing thoughts, or muscle tension, not panic attacks. Your body is trying to prepare for “danger” that doesn’t exist — an ancient stress response stuck in modern overdrive. The solution isn’t suppressing it, but retraining your nervous system: steady breathing, grounding exercises, regular exercise, and talking through worries instead of containing them. Anxiety means your mind is alert, not broken. When you calm your body, your thoughts begin to follow."),
    QA(id: 7, question: "What’s the difference between a midlife slump and depression?", answer: "A midlife slump feels like questioning purpose; depression feels like losing it altogether. One prompts curiosity — “Is this all there is?” — the other drains all energy and hope. Both can coexist, but the difference is vitality: a slump invites change, depression resists it. If every day feels heavy and even small goals feel impossible, that’s depression’s footprint. Therapy, new challenges, or reconnecting with meaning can turn that slump into a renewal phase. Midlife isn’t decline — it’s your second growth curve waiting to be activated."),
    QA(id: 8, question: "Can mental‑health issues show up as physical problems?", answer: "Absolutely. Mind and body are intertwined. Chronic stress can cause headaches, stomach pain, muscle tension, and heart palpitations. When emotional pressure has no outlet, it manifests physically. Men often ignore emotional pain until their body screams for attention. A full check‑up is smart — but if results are fine, address stress directly: breathwork, journaling, or talking with someone trained to listen. Healing your mental state often eases physical tension too. The body whispers before it shouts — listen early."),
    QA(id: 9, question: "How do I know when it’s time to seek professional help?", answer: "When symptoms start limiting daily life — motivation, sleep, relationships, or work performance — that’s the sign. You don’t need to hit rock bottom. Think of therapy like preventive maintenance. Just as you’d see a mechanic for your car’s early noise, see a therapist when your mind feels off‑balance. Early support shortens recovery and deepens insight. You’re not weak for seeking help; you’re wise enough to maintain your most powerful engine — your mind."),
    QA(id: 10, question: "Could unresolved past stress or trauma resurface years later?", answer: "Yes. Unprocessed memories and emotions often stay stored in your body and re‑emerge under pressure — during relationship issues, loss, or burnout. It’s your system’s way of saying “now I’m safe enough to heal.” Revisiting the past with guidance doesn’t mean reliving pain — it means releasing its grip. Trauma therapy, mindfulness, and self‑compassion rebuild emotional safety. Healing old wounds in midlife can create more freedom than ever before. The past shaped you; it doesn’t have to control you."),
  ]),
  QATheme(title: "Stigma, Identity & Masculinity", items: [
    QA(id: 11, question: "Is it weak or unmanly to admit I need help or go to therapy?", answer: "Not at all. Real strength isn’t about never breaking — it’s about having the courage to rebuild when life hits hard. Therapy isn’t a confession of failure; it’s a training ground for resilience. You wouldn’t call a man weak for hiring a coach to improve his body — the same applies to the mind. Modern masculinity is evolving: power now means self‑awareness, emotional control, and growth. The men who lead with openness inspire others to do the same. Vulnerability is not weakness; it’s leadership under pressure."),
    QA(id: 12, question: "Why is it so hard for men to open up about feelings?", answer: "Because most of us were taught early on to suppress emotion — “toughen up,” “don’t cry,” “handle it yourself.” Those messages build emotional walls that become habits. Opening up feels foreign, even dangerous. But expressing emotion doesn’t make you soft; it makes you human. Start small: name one feeling per day without judging it. Over time, that emotional vocabulary becomes your armor, not your weakness. Speaking honestly is how you begin to truly breathe again."),
    QA(id: 13, question: "How can I open up to my partner or friends without feeling judged?", answer: "Start with honesty, not drama. You don’t have to unload everything — just share a snapshot: “Lately I’ve been more tired and tense than usual.” Keep it calm and factual. You’ll be surprised how often people respond with care, not criticism. Choose one person who listens, not fixes. Vulnerability is like a muscle — use it gradually. When you express yourself openly, you give permission for others to do the same. Connection grows when courage replaces performance."),
    QA(id: 14, question: "Will people think less of me if I admit I’m struggling mentally?", answer: "Maybe some will — but those people likely misunderstand what mental strength truly is. The world is shifting fast: emotional intelligence is now a core leadership skill, not a flaw. Most people will actually respect your honesty, especially if you handle it with quiet confidence. Everyone struggles. The difference is that some hide it, while others face it head‑on. By showing up authentically, you make it safer for others to do the same. That’s real influence."),
    QA(id: 15, question: "I’ve always been the strong one — what does it mean if I can’t cope now?", answer: "It means you’ve been strong for a long time, and your mind is asking for maintenance. Strength isn’t infinite; it needs recharging. When you’ve carried others, led teams, or held your family together, your nervous system can quietly wear down. Struggling now doesn’t erase your past resilience — it proves you’ve reached your human limit. What matters is what you do next: rest, reflect, rebuild. Vulnerability isn’t collapse — it’s recovery in progress. You’re recalibrating."),
    QA(id: 16, question: "How can I overcome the stigma of seeking therapy or taking mental health seriously?", answer: "Reframe what therapy means. It’s not “fixing brokenness,” it’s upgrading your emotional software. Think of it as coaching for the mind — a process that helps you perform, lead, and connect better. Many high‑performing men now see therapy as strategic, not shameful. If others don’t understand, that’s their conditioning talking, not truth. Every time you normalize mental health in your circle, you chip away at outdated stigma. The ripple effect starts with you — one conversation at a time."),
    QA(id: 17, question: "How do I handle guilt for needing rest or time off when others depend on me?", answer: "Rest is not withdrawal — it’s renewal. When you rest, you refuel your capacity to show up. Guilt usually comes from old programming that equates productivity with worth. But a burnt‑out man can’t lead effectively, love deeply, or think clearly. Take rest as responsibility, not indulgence. Set boundaries, unplug, breathe. You’ll come back sharper and calmer. Those who depend on you deserve your best — and that includes a version of you that’s not running on fumes."),
    QA(id: 18, question: "How can I redefine masculinity for myself in today’s world?", answer: "Drop the outdated checklist — toughness, control, silence — and replace it with emotional depth, purpose, and compassion. Modern masculinity is about balance: strong enough to protect, humble enough to listen, brave enough to feel. Redefine success not by how much you suppress, but by how deeply you connect — with yourself, your loved ones, and your mission. That’s the new alpha: calm, grounded, emotionally fluent, and unshakably authentic."),
    QA(id: 19, question: "What if people at work see me differently if I talk about mental health?", answer: "Control the narrative by how you speak about it. Keep it simple and professional: “I’m taking steps to improve my focus and wellbeing.” You don’t owe anyone details. Leaders who normalize mental health often gain respect. If someone reacts negatively, it says more about their discomfort than your choices. Mental health is private healthcare, not public gossip. Protect it with confidence."),
    QA(id: 20, question: "How can I lead by example in breaking the silence around men’s mental health?", answer: "Start with honesty in small circles — friends, colleagues, family. Share not only struggles but also what’s helping you. Mention that you’ve talked to someone, taken time for reflection, or started a morning routine that helps. People listen to actions more than words. When a man leads with openness, it gives others permission to drop their armor too. You don’t need to be perfect; you need to be real."),
  ]),
  QATheme(title: "Stress, Anxiety & Depression", items: [
    QA(id: 21, question: "I’ve tried to ‘deal with it myself’ — exercise, work, distraction — but nothing helps. What now?", answer: "That’s a sign your coping strategies have reached their limit, not that you’ve failed. When effort stops working, it usually means you’re treating symptoms, not causes. Time to slow down and talk it out. A therapist or coach can help you uncover what’s really driving the tension. Healing often starts when you stop “doing” and start listening inwardly. You’ve already proven discipline; now practice receptiveness. It’s not weakness — it’s emotional intelligence in action."),
    QA(id: 22, question: "Could job loss, financial stress or uncertainty trigger depression?", answer: "Absolutely. Stability is a core psychological need, and when it’s shaken, self‑worth often feels threatened. Depression can follow prolonged uncertainty or identity loss. Shift focus from control to adaptability: daily structure, small wins, movement, and conversations with trusted peers. Seek guidance before isolation deepens. Financial recovery is external; emotional recovery is internal — and both are possible with steady, honest action. You’re rebuilding, not restarting."),
    QA(id: 23, question: "Can anger, irritability or short temper be signs of depression in men?", answer: "Yes — in many men, anger is depression turned outward. It’s the body’s way of saying “I’m overwhelmed.” Instead of judging it, view anger as a signal to pause. Behind it often lies exhaustion or sadness you haven’t felt safe expressing. Physical release helps: deep breathing, workouts, a shout into a pillow. Then ask: What’s really hurting me right now? Naming it breaks the pattern. Anger managed with awareness becomes strength."),
    QA(id: 24, question: "What’s the best way to calm racing thoughts or daily anxiety?", answer: "Ground your body first. When the nervous system feels safe, the mind follows. Try this: breathe in for 4 seconds, hold 2, exhale 6. Repeat until your shoulders drop. Limit caffeine and doom‑scrolling; walk outside daily; write down worries to move them out of your head. Anxiety feeds on uncertainty — so create small certainties like morning routines. You’re retraining your brain, one breath at a time."),
    QA(id: 25, question: "How can I stop feeling like I’m failing at everything lately?", answer: "Separate self‑worth from performance. The world teaches men to measure value by results, but setbacks are part of growth, not proof of failure. Reframe mistakes as feedback. Make a daily list of three things you did well — no matter how small. Success begins with self‑respect, not perfection. Progress isn’t linear; it’s lived experience shaping you into a wiser, steadier man."),
    QA(id: 26, question: "Can long‑term stress really harm my body?", answer: "Yes — chronic stress floods your system with cortisol, raising blood pressure, affecting sleep, focus, and immunity. The good news: your body heals quickly once balance returns. Counter stress chemistry with its opposites — deep breathing, laughter, hydration, sunlight, stretching, good food, and connection. Think of it as recalibrating your internal battery. Rest repairs you at a cellular level."),
    QA(id: 27, question: "How do I know if anxiety medication or therapy is right for me?", answer: "If anxiety interferes with sleep, focus, or daily function, explore options. Therapy addresses the why; medication stabilizes the how. Many men benefit from both short‑term medication and long‑term coping skills. See your GP or psychiatrist for honest discussion — no commitment, just clarity. The goal isn’t dependency; it’s relief while you retrain your mind."),
    QA(id: 28, question: "How can I prevent burnout at work?", answer: "Recognize early signs: constant fatigue, irritability, cynicism, or loss of motivation. Set micro‑boundaries — no emails after a cutoff, regular breaks, breathing resets between meetings. Fuel your body, move daily, and protect sleep. Reconnect with why you work — purpose prevents burnout more than willpower. Sustainable men pace themselves."),
    QA(id: 29, question: "How can I deal with constant pressure to provide or perform?", answer: "Reframe pressure as purpose — you’re not carrying it alone. Talk openly with those who rely on you; shared responsibility lightens the load. Create pressure‑free zones: hobbies, exercise, moments of stillness where no one needs anything from you. True providers build security through emotional presence as much as income. Calm focus outperforms anxious hustle."),
    QA(id: 30, question: "What if I feel fine some days and hopeless others — is that normal?", answer: "Completely. Healing isn’t linear; emotions move in waves. Some days are setbacks, not failures. Think of mental health like fitness — you don’t lose strength from one rest day. Track patterns, not perfection. When lows come, remind yourself they always pass. Anchor to routines and people who ground you. That’s resilience, not weakness."),
  ]),
  QATheme(title: "Relationships & Communication", items: [
    QA(id: 31, question: "How can I talk to my partner about mental health without worrying I’ll push them away?", answer: "Start from honesty, not apology. Use calm language like, “I’ve been feeling off lately, and I want to share it, not make you fix it.” That invites understanding instead of tension. Most partners want to support but don’t know how unless you guide them. Let them listen — not solve. Vulnerability expressed with balance and calm tone deepens trust. Relationships grow through shared truth."),
    QA(id: 32, question: "What if my partner or friends don’t understand what I’m going through?", answer: "Most people mean well but lack the vocabulary for mental health. Don’t expect perfect empathy; aim for honest communication. Say, “I don’t need advice — I just need space to talk.” If they still can’t connect, seek outside support: therapy, men’s groups, or online spaces where you feel seen. Teaching them patiently often bridges the gap. Compassion goes both ways."),
    QA(id: 33, question: "How can I stop taking my stress out on the people I care about?", answer: "When stress builds, the mind looks for release — often at home. Before reacting, pause. Breathe. Ask: Am I angry at them, or at my day? Create a cooldown routine after work: walk, shower, music, anything that resets energy. If you slip up, own it quickly: “Sorry, I was stressed — not at you.” Emotional control is repair done fast."),
    QA(id: 34, question: "How can I support a friend who’s struggling but won’t open up?", answer: "Show consistent presence, not pressure. Instead of asking, “What’s wrong?” say, “I’m here if you ever want to talk — no judgment.” Share something small from your own life; it signals safety. Keep checking in with kindness, not force. Men often open up slowly once they know it’s safe. Support is being steady, not saving them."),
    QA(id: 35, question: "How can I balance being a strong partner while still taking care of my own mental health?", answer: "True strength includes knowing your limits. You can’t pour from an empty tank. Set boundaries kindly — “I need some quiet time tonight so I can show up better tomorrow.” A healthy partner respects that. Strength isn’t nonstop giving; it’s sustainable giving. Self‑care multiplies love through balance and clarity."),
    QA(id: 36, question: "How do I rebuild closeness after emotional distance or conflict?", answer: "Start with curiosity, not blame. Ask, “How have you been feeling about us lately?” Listen — really listen. Don’t rush to defend or explain. Empathy repairs faster than logic. Then, share one truth about your own feelings calmly. Consistency, small gestures, and honest effort reignite trust. Rebuild the bridge one calm talk at a time."),
    QA(id: 37, question: "How can I improve communication when I tend to shut down during arguments?", answer: "When emotions rise, your nervous system shifts into defense mode. The goal is regulation, not silence. Tell your partner, “I need a short break to cool off — I’ll come back when I can think clearly.” Then keep that promise. During the pause, breathe, move, or journal. Returning shows maturity and reliability. That’s communication with integrity."),
  ]),
  QATheme(title: "Work, Purpose & Midlife Challenges", items: [
    QA(id: 38, question: "Is it normal to feel lost or unmotivated in my 40s or 50s?", answer: "Completely. Many men hit a “meaning reset” around this age. It’s not failure — it’s evolution. You’ve spent years building, achieving, providing; now your soul asks, “What’s next?” Motivation changes when purpose changes. Instead of chasing the old spark, explore new ones — contribution, creativity, mentoring, balance. Midlife isn’t decline; it’s recalibration toward authenticity."),
    QA(id: 39, question: "How do I handle burnout when I can’t afford to slow down?", answer: "Burnout isn’t solved by quitting; it’s managed by rebalancing. Micro‑recovery keeps you functional: stretch breaks, deep breathing between tasks, proper meals, real sleep. If possible, delegate small tasks or renegotiate unrealistic deadlines. Say “no” with respect — it’s leadership, not rebellion. Sustainable success requires rest as strategy."),
    QA(id: 40, question: "How can I find purpose again when I feel like I’ve plateaued?", answer: "Purpose often hides behind curiosity. Ask: What do I miss doing for me? Don’t look for one grand mission; focus on meaningful micro‑purposes. When you give energy to things that align with your values, motivation returns. Purpose unfolds when you reconnect with what makes you feel alive, useful, and at peace."),
    QA(id: 41, question: "How do I cope with career pressure or feeling “behind” in life?", answer: "Comparison poisons clarity. Everyone’s path unfolds differently — especially after 35. You’re not behind; you’re evolving. Pressure to “catch up” often comes from outdated timelines. Redefine success by alignment, not appearances. Focus on progress, not pace. Real success is inner peace, not outer approval."),
    QA(id: 42, question: "How can I deal with identity loss after career change, divorce, or major life shifts?", answer: "Big transitions shake identity — especially for men raised to define themselves by role or achievement. You’re not broken; you’re rebuilding. Identity is fluid, not fixed. Explore new aspects of yourself through journaling, therapy, or new experiences. Ask, Who am I when I’m not performing? This is reinvention, not collapse."),
    QA(id: 43, question: "How do I manage the constant work‑life balance battle?", answer: "Balance isn’t static — it’s dynamic adjustment. Some days work wins; others, family or rest does. Protect sacred time for recovery and connection. Put phone‑free hours in your day. Productivity means nothing without presence. Work smarter, rest deliberately, and measure success by harmony, not hours."),
    QA(id: 44, question: "How can I rediscover motivation after years of grinding?", answer: "Motivation fades when you run on obligation instead of inspiration. Reconnect to why you began — then adapt that why to who you are now. Challenge yourself with new learning goals or mentorship roles; growth reignites passion. Trade autopilot for intention, and drive returns naturally."),
    QA(id: 45, question: "How do I deal with the fear of aging — mentally and physically?", answer: "Aging isn’t loss; it’s refinement. You’re not losing potential — you’re gaining perspective. Fear comes from resisting change. Focus on what strengthens you: mobility, mental clarity, relationships, self‑respect. Stay curious and keep moving. The goal isn’t to stay young — it’s to stay engaged. Awareness is mastery, not decline."),
  ]),
  QATheme(title: "Healing, Therapy & Lifestyle Tools", items: [
    QA(id: 46, question: "How do I know which kind of therapy is right for me?", answer: "There’s no one‑size‑fits‑all. CBT helps reframe negative thinking. Talk therapy helps process emotions and patterns. Mindfulness‑based approaches reduce anxiety by grounding the body. Choose what you need most: structure, exploration, or calm. You can switch — that’s normal. The right therapist feels like a good coach: supportive, challenging, and safe. The goal isn’t labels — it’s progress."),
    QA(id: 47, question: "Is it too late to start therapy in my 40s or 50s?", answer: "Never. Therapy often works faster in midlife because you bring self‑awareness and life experience. The patterns you built can now be restructured consciously. Many men find therapy life‑changing — less about crisis, more about clarity. Think of it as upgrading your inner operating system after decades of old code."),
    QA(id: 48, question: "What daily habits actually improve mental health long‑term?", answer: "Consistency beats intensity. Five pillars: Sleep 7–8 hours, same schedule. Movement daily. Nutrition that stabilizes blood sugar, plus hydration. Stillness: 10 minutes of breathing, prayer, or meditation. Connection: one meaningful interaction daily. Add sunlight, purpose, and laughter. Small rituals compound into stability."),
    QA(id: 49, question: "How can meditation or breathwork help anxiety?", answer: "Breathing tells your nervous system you’re safe. Slow your exhale; cortisol drops, clarity rises. Meditation strengthens focus, reducing overthinking. Start small: one minute of slow breathing before sleep or after waking. Don’t chase “empty mind” — aim for present awareness. Over time, fewer anxious spikes and faster recovery."),
    QA(id: 50, question: "How can I combine physical fitness and mental wellness?", answer: "They’re inseparable. Exercise releases endorphins and dopamine — natural mood stabilizers. Choose activities that calm and challenge — walking, yoga, strength training, swimming. Avoid punishment; train to feel alive. Regular movement is therapy in motion — strengthening confidence, discipline, and emotional stability."),
    QA(id: 51, question: "What can I do when motivation disappears?", answer: "Motivation fades when you over‑focus on the destination and forget the process. Simplify. Set micro‑goals: today I’ll just start. Action creates momentum; momentum reignites motivation. Don’t wait to feel inspired — move first, feelings follow. Reconnect with meaning — who benefits when you show up?"),
    QA(id: 52, question: "How can I build emotional resilience?", answer: "Resilience grows through reflection, not resistance. After every setback, ask: What is this teaching me? That reframes pain into purpose. Build routines that ground you: journaling, gratitude, mindfulness. Resilience isn’t never falling — it’s recovering faster each time. Strength is mastering your response."),
    QA(id: 53, question: "How can I make self‑care feel less “soft” and more masculine?", answer: "Redefine it as self‑respect. It’s training your mind like your body. Sleep, boundaries, nutrition, and reflection are tactical moves for high performance. True warriors rest between battles. Treat self‑care as leadership — the calm, clear man rises above chaos."),
    QA(id: 54, question: "How long does it take to feel better once I start working on mental health?", answer: "Timelines vary, but small relief often shows within weeks — better sleep, calmer mornings, fewer anxiety spikes. Real transformation builds over months. Progress feels like steadiness, not euphoria. Stay patient; consistency pays off. Healing is integration — habits and awareness that make peace your default."),
    QA(id: 55, question: "How do I stay on track when I relapse or lose progress?", answer: "Relapse isn’t failure — it’s feedback. Healing is cyclical; setbacks show where old patterns still live. Instead of shame, use curiosity: What triggered this? Adjust, don’t abandon. Keep routines simple and restart fast. Talk it through with someone trusted. You’re starting from experience, not zero."),
  ]),
  QATheme(title: "Growth, Motivation & Loneliness", items: [
    QA(id: 56, question: "How do I rebuild confidence after years of anxiety or setbacks?", answer: "Confidence returns through small, consistent wins. Start where you have control — a morning routine, a workout, a project you finish. Each kept promise tells your brain, I can trust myself again. Avoid comparing your current self to your past peak. Confidence is a muscle: rebuild with discipline, rest, and self‑respect."),
    QA(id: 57, question: "How can I handle loneliness even when surrounded by people?", answer: "Loneliness isn’t about company; it’s about connection. Many men feel unseen because they hide their inner world. Open one layer deeper with someone you trust. Join groups where authenticity is welcomed. Reconnect with yourself — journaling, meditation, purposeful solitude. When you accept your own company, others connect more easily."),
    QA(id: 58, question: "How do I find motivation when life feels repetitive?", answer: "Stagnation drains drive. The antidote is novelty — learn a new skill, hobby, or goal. The brain releases dopamine with challenge, not comfort. Keep routines for stability but add small adventures. Revisit your values — what excites or matters now? Momentum follows curiosity."),
    QA(id: 59, question: "How can I turn pain or failure into personal growth?", answer: "Pain reveals what matters. Ask not “Why me?” but “What’s this teaching me?” That transforms suffering into wisdom. Reflect on gains — strength, empathy, perspective. Use experience to help others, or channel it into creativity or training. Scars don’t define you — they prove survival."),
    QA(id: 60, question: "How do I maintain long‑term mental health once I start feeling better?", answer: "Treat mental health like fitness — ongoing practice. Keep the basics: sleep, exercise, nutrition, and emotional check‑ins. Continue journaling or therapy even when you’re fine. Watch for early signs — irritability, withdrawal, fatigue — and act early. Prevention is easier than repair. The goal is steady resilience."),
  ]),
];
